          "title": "Statute of Limitations in Georgia",
          "content": "In Georgia, the statute of limitations for most personal injury claims is **two years** from the date of the injury [1]. This means that if you've been injured due to someone else's negligence, you generally have a two-year window to file a lawsuit in civil court. This deadline is enshrined in Georgia law, specifically O.C.G.A. \u00a7 9-3-33, and applies to a wide array of cases including car accidents, slip and falls, and dog bites. However, it's crucial to understand that this two-year period is not absolute, and certain exceptions and tolling rules can either extend or shorten this timeframe. For instance, claims involving property damage have a longer four-year statute of limitations [1]. Medical malpractice cases also typically adhere to the two-year rule, but they are subject to a five-year statute of repose, which acts as an absolute bar to claims regardless of when the injury was discovered [1]. Wrongful death claims generally follow the two-year rule from the date of death, but this period can be tolled, or paused, for up to six years if criminal proceedings related to the death are ongoing [1]. Product liability cases also have a two-year statute of limitations, with a potential ten-year statute of repose [1].\n\nTolling provisions can temporarily suspend the running of the statute of limitations. Common examples include cases involving minors, where the two-year clock does not begin until the injured individual turns 18 years old. Similarly, if a person is deemed mentally incapacitated, the statute of limitations may be tolled during the period of their incapacity. In situations where the injury is not immediately apparent, Georgia's discovery rule may apply, meaning the clock starts when the injury is discovered or reasonably should have been discovered. However, these exceptions are complex and require careful legal analysis. Missing this critical deadline almost invariably results in the forfeiture of your right to pursue compensation, making it imperative to consult with an experienced personal injury attorney as soon as possible after an accident to understand the specific deadlines applicable to your case.",
