          "title": "Negligence Rules in Georgia",
          "content": "Georgia operates under a **modified comparative negligence** rule with a **50% bar** [2]. This legal principle dictates how damages are awarded in personal injury cases where both parties may share some degree of fault for an accident. Under this rule, an injured party can only recover damages if their own fault is determined to be less than 50% [2]. If a jury finds you 49% at fault, you can still recover 51% of your damages. However, if your fault is assessed at 50% or greater, you are completely barred from recovering any compensation from the other party [2]. This system is a middle ground between 'contributory negligence,' where any fault on the part of the injured person bars recovery entirely, and 'pure comparative negligence,' where an injured party can recover damages even if they are 99% at fault, albeit significantly reduced. The determination of fault percentages is a critical aspect of any personal injury claim in Georgia, as it directly impacts the amount of compensation you can receive. Insurance companies and defense attorneys frequently leverage this rule during negotiations, often attempting to assign a higher percentage of fault to the injured party to reduce their payout obligations. Therefore, understanding this rule is paramount for anyone pursuing a personal injury claim in Georgia.",
