          "title": "Statute of Limitations in Delaware",
          "content": "In Delaware, the statute of limitations sets a strict deadline for filing a personal injury lawsuit. For most personal injury cases, this crucial deadline is **two years** from the date the injury occurred [1]. This two-year period applies to a wide range of personal injury claims, including those arising from car accidents, premises liability (such as slip-and-fall incidents), product liability, and cases involving negligence or intentional misconduct [1].\\n\\nHowever, there are specific exceptions and nuances to this general rule that are vital to understand. For instance, in medical malpractice cases, the general rule is also two years from the date of injury. Yet, if the injury was not immediately discoverable, and could not have been discovered with reasonable diligence, the injured party may have up to **three years** from the date of injury to file a lawsuit under the 'discovery rule' [1].\\n\\nSpecial considerations also apply to minors. If a minor suffers a personal injury, they generally have three years from their 18th birthday to file a lawsuit [1]. However, medical malpractice claims involving children younger than six years old have a specific rule: the lawsuit must be filed by their sixth birthday or when the general medical malpractice statute of limitations expires, whichever is later [1].\\n\\nAnother important exception involves the defendant's absence from the state. If the party responsible for the injury is outside Delaware when the injury occurs, or leaves the state afterward, the statute of limitations clock may be 'tolled' (temporarily stopped) for the period of their absence [1]. This means the time they are out of state does not count towards the two-year limit. \\n\\nClaims against municipalities (cities or counties) in Delaware also have unique notice requirements and potentially shorter deadlines. For example, some municipalities may require written notice of an injury within one year of the incident [1]. Failure to provide this notice can bar a lawsuit, even if the general statute of limitations has not expired. It is crucial to consult with a Delaware personal injury attorney to understand how these exceptions apply to your specific case and to ensure all deadlines are met.\\n\\n",
