          "title": "Statute of Limitations in Florida",
          "content": "The statute of limitations for most personal injury claims in Florida is two years from the date of the injury. This two-year period applies to accidents that occurred on or after March 24, 2023. For incidents that took place before this date, the previous statute of limitations of four years still applies. This critical deadline is governed by Florida Statute \u00a7 95.11(5)(a), as amended by House Bill 837, a significant tort reform law. It is crucial to understand that this two-year clock typically begins on the exact date of the accident, not when the injury is discovered, medical treatment concludes, or an insurance claim is resolved. Failing to file a lawsuit within this strict timeframe will almost certainly lead to the dismissal of your case, regardless of the merits. There are very limited exceptions that may 'toll' or pause this deadline. These include cases involving minors, where the statute may be tolled until they reach 18, although this can vary by case type. Legal incapacity, such as being in a coma or suffering from severe cognitive disability, can also toll the statute during the period of incapacity, requiring strong evidence of the individual's inability to act. The 'discovery rule' may apply in rare circumstances, primarily in medical malpractice or latent injury cases where the harm was not immediately apparent, allowing the clock to start when the injury was or should have been discovered. This rule generally does not apply to typical car accident claims. Lastly, if the defendant actively concealed facts preventing the discovery of the injury or its cause, the statute might be tolled until the concealment is revealed. These exceptions are narrow, challenging to prove, and courts apply them with skepticism. It is always safest to assume the standard two-year deadline applies and to consult with an attorney promptly to protect your rights.",
