          "title": "Negligence Rules in Florida",
          "content": "Florida operates under a modified comparative negligence system, a significant change enacted by House Bill 837 on March 24, 2023. Prior to this, Florida was a 'pure comparative negligence' state. Under the current modified comparative negligence rule, an injured party can recover damages even if they are partially at fault for the accident, but their recovery is barred if they are found to be more than 50% responsible for their own injuries. If a plaintiff is found to be 50% or less at fault, their total compensation will be reduced by their percentage of fault. For example, if you are awarded $100,000 in damages but are found to be 20% at fault, you would only receive $80,000. This system aims to ensure that individuals are held accountable for their share of responsibility while still allowing them to seek compensation if their fault is not the primary cause. This rule applies to most personal injury cases, though claims based on medical negligence are an exception. Understanding this rule is crucial, as it directly impacts the amount of compensation you can receive. It is vital to have an experienced personal injury attorney who can effectively argue your case and minimize your assigned percentage of fault.",
