          "title": "Statute of Limitations in Iowa",
          "content": "In Iowa, the statute of limitations for most personal injury claims is generally two years from the date of the injury [1]. This two-year period applies to a wide range of cases, including those arising from auto accidents, dangerous products (product liability), dangerous properties (premises liability), and intentional misconduct such as assault or defamation. It is crucial to adhere to this deadline, as failing to file a lawsuit within this timeframe typically results in the forfeiture of your right to pursue compensation. \n\nIowa also recognizes the 'discovery rule,' which can extend the statute of limitations in cases where the injury is not immediately apparent. Under this rule, the two-year clock begins when you discover, or reasonably should have discovered, your injury [1]. However, it's important to note that statutes of repose can place an outside limit on this extension. For instance, product liability cases have a 15-year statute of repose, and premises liability cases typically have an 8-10 year limit [1].\n\nMedical malpractice cases have a specific statute of limitations: two years from the date of discovery of the injury or death, with a six-year statute of repose from the date of the malpractice. An exception exists if a foreign object is accidentally left in a patient's body, in which case the six-year repose period does not apply. For minors injured by medical malpractice, a lawsuit must be filed by their 10th birthday or the general two-year discovery rule deadline, whichever is later [1]. Additionally, if a defendant leaves Iowa or cannot be identified, or if the injured person is legally disabled (e.g., a minor or someone with a mental illness), the statute of limitations may be extended [1].",
