          "content": "Maine follows a 'modified comparative negligence' rule, specifically the 50% bar rule, as outlined in Maine Revised Statutes Title 14, Section 156. Under this system, you can still recover damages in a personal injury lawsuit even if you were partially at fault for the accident that caused your injuries. However, your degree of fault must be less than the fault of the other party or parties involved. If a jury determines that you are 50% or more responsible for the accident, you are completely barred from recovering any compensation whatsoever. If your fault is determined to be 49% or less, you can recover damages, but your total award will be reduced by a percentage equal to your share of the blame. For example, if you are found to be 20% at fault in a car accident and your total damages amount to $100,000, your final compensation will be reduced by 20%, leaving you with an $80,000 settlement. This rule makes determining fault a critical aspect of any personal injury case in Maine, as insurance companies will often try to shift the blame onto the victim to reduce or eliminate their financial liability.",
