          "title": "Statute of Limitations in Minnesota",
          "content": "In Minnesota, the statute of limitations for most personal injury cases is **six years** from the date of the injury. This is outlined in Minn. Stat. section 541.05.1(5) (2025). However, there are several exceptions to this general rule. For instance, medical malpractice lawsuits typically have a **four-year** statute of limitations from the date of the healthcare provider's mistake (Minn. Stat. section 541.076 (2025)). Wrongful death lawsuits generally must be filed within **three years** of the deceased person's death (Minn. Stat. section 573.02 (2025)). Cases involving libel, slander, assault, battery, or false imprisonment have a shorter deadline of **two years** (Minn. Stat. section 541.07 (2025)).\n\nProduct liability lawsuits also have varying deadlines. If the claim is based on negligence, the standard six-year period applies. However, if the claim is based on strict liability, the deadline is **four years** (Minn. Stat. sections 541.05.1 and 541.05.2 (2025)).\n\nMinnesota employs the \"some damage\" rule rather than the \"discovery rule\" for determining when the statute of limitations begins. This means the clock starts ticking from the date you suffered at least some harm that entitles you to a legal remedy, not necessarily when you discovered the full extent of the injury or the responsible party. This distinction is particularly important in cases involving latent injuries, such as those from toxic chemicals or medical malpractice, where health problems may develop over time.\n\nExceptions to the statute of limitations exist, such as when the injured person is under a \"legal disability\" (e.g., a minor or incapacitated by mental illness). In such cases, the deadline may be extended, typically for one year after the disability ends, with a maximum extension of five years for mental illness. If the at-fault person is not in Minnesota, the time they are out of state may be subtracted from the calculation, provided the plaintiff diligently attempted to locate and serve them. Additionally, if the defendant engaged in \"fraudulent concealment\" of their responsibility, the delay caused by this behavior will not count towards the statute of limitations.",
          "subsections": [
            {
              "title": "Why This Deadline Matters",
              "content": "The statute of limitations is a critical deadline that can significantly impact your ability to seek compensation for your injuries. If you fail to file your lawsuit within the prescribed timeframe, you will likely lose your right to have your case heard in court, regardless of the severity of your injuries or the clarity of the other party's fault. This means you could be left without any legal recourse for your medical expenses, lost wages, pain, and suffering. Insurance companies are well aware of these legal deadlines and may use them to their advantage during settlement negotiations. If you approach the deadline without filing a lawsuit, your bargaining power diminishes considerably, as the insurance company knows you may lose the option to pursue legal action. Therefore, it is crucial to act promptly after an accident to protect your legal rights and ensure you have sufficient time to negotiate a fair settlement or file a lawsuit if necessary. Delaying action can lead to the forfeiture of your claim and prevent you from recovering the compensation you deserve. It is always advisable to consult with a personal injury attorney as soon as possible to understand the specific deadlines applicable to your case and to ensure all necessary steps are taken within the legal timeframe."
            }
          ]
