          "title": "What to Do After an Accident in Missouri",
          "content": "Immediately following a personal injury accident in Missouri, your actions can significantly impact the success of any future claim. It is crucial to follow a step-by-step guide to protect your health and legal rights:\n\n1.  **Ensure Safety and Seek Medical Attention**: Your immediate priority should be your safety and the safety of others. Move to a safe location if possible. Even if you feel fine, seek medical attention promptly. Some injuries, especially those to the head or spine, may not manifest symptoms immediately. A medical evaluation creates an official record of your injuries, which is vital for your claim [25].\n2.  **Report the Accident**: Depending on the type of accident, reporting requirements vary:\n    *   **Car Accidents**: In Missouri, you should contact the police to report the accident, especially if there are injuries, significant property damage, or if the other driver is uncooperative. A police report can provide an objective account of the incident [26].\n    *   **Slip and Fall**: Report the incident to the property owner or manager immediately. Request that an incident report be filed and obtain a copy. Documenting the unsafe condition is critical.\n    *   **Workplace Injuries**: Report the injury to your supervisor or employer as soon as possible, following company procedures for workplace accidents.\n3.  **Document the Scene**: If you are able, gather as much evidence as possible at the scene:\n    *   **Photographs and Videos**: Use your phone to take pictures and videos of the accident scene, vehicle damage, visible injuries, road conditions, traffic signs, and any other relevant details. The more visual documentation, the better [15].\n    *   **Witness Information**: Collect contact information (names, phone numbers, email addresses) from any witnesses. Their testimony can be invaluable.\n    *   **Exchange Information**: For car accidents, exchange insurance and contact information with all involved parties. Do not admit fault or discuss the specifics of the accident with anyone other than law enforcement or your attorney.\n4.  **Keep Detailed Records**: Maintain a comprehensive file of all documents related to your accident and injuries. This includes medical bills, treatment records, prescription receipts, lost wage statements, and any communication with insurance companies. These records will be essential for calculating your damages.\n5.  **Avoid Discussing Your Case**: Do not give recorded statements to insurance adjusters without consulting an attorney. Insurance companies may try to use your statements against you to minimize your claim. Avoid posting details about your accident or injuries on social media, as these posts can be used to undermine your case.\n6.  **Consult a Personal Injury Attorney**: Given Missouri's five-year statute of limitations for most personal injury claims, it is crucial to contact an attorney as soon as possible [13]. An attorney can help you understand your rights, navigate the legal process, gather evidence, negotiate with insurance companies, and ensure all deadlines are met. They can also help counter tactics by insurers to shift blame or reduce your settlement [15]."
