          "title": "Statute of Limitations in Montana",
          "content": "In Montana, the statute of limitations for most personal injury cases is **three years** from the date the injury occurred [1]. This means that a lawsuit must be filed within this timeframe, or the injured party may lose their right to seek compensation. This three-year period applies to a wide range of personal injury claims, including those arising from car accidents, truck accidents, slip-and-fall incidents, and product liability cases [1].\n\nHowever, there are exceptions to this general rule. For instance, lawsuits involving certain **intentional torts**, such as assault, battery, defamation, and false imprisonment, have a shorter statute of limitations of **two years** [1].\n\n**Wrongful death** claims generally have a **three-year** statute of limitations from the date of death. However, if the death resulted from homicide, the deadline is extended to **10 years** from the date of death [1].\n\n**Medical malpractice** cases also have specific timelines. A medical malpractice lawsuit must be filed within **two years** from the date of injury or the date the injury was discovered (or should have been discovered with reasonable diligence). There is also a **five-year statute of repose**, meaning that regardless of discovery, a medical malpractice claim cannot be filed more than five years after the act causing the injury. This five-year period can be tolled if the healthcare provider knowingly concealed the malpractice [1]. Special rules apply to very young children (under four years old) injured by medical malpractice, where the limitation period doesn't begin until the child's eighth birthday or death, whichever comes first [1].\n\nMontana also recognizes the **discovery rule**, which can extend the statute of limitations. Under this rule, the clock for filing a lawsuit does not begin until the injured party discovers their injury, or reasonably should have discovered it through diligent effort [1].",
          "subsections": [
            {
              "title": "Why This Deadline Matters",
              "content": "The statute of limitations is a critical legal deadline that can significantly impact a personal injury claim. Failing to file a lawsuit within the prescribed timeframe, without a valid exception, will result in the permanent loss of the right to pursue compensation for damages [1]. Insurance companies are well aware of these deadlines and may use tactics to delay settlement negotiations, hoping the statute of limitations will expire. Once the deadline passes, the injured party loses their leverage, and the insurance company is no longer obligated to negotiate or pay a settlement. Therefore, it is crucial for accident victims to act promptly and seek legal advice to ensure their claim is filed within the statutory period. The urgency of adhering to this deadline cannot be overstated, as it directly affects the viability of a personal injury claim and the ability to recover for medical expenses, lost wages, pain, and suffering.\n\n### References\n[1] Nolo.com. Montana Personal Injury Laws and Statutes of Limitations. https://www.nolo.com/legal-encyclopedia/montana-personal-injury-laws-and-statutes-of-limitations.html"
            }
          ]
