          "title": "Statute of Limitations in New Mexico",
          "content": "In New Mexico, the statute of limitations for most personal injury claims is three years from the date of the incident. This crucial legal deadline is codified under NM Stat. \u00a7 37-1-8. This means that if you suffer an injury due to another party's negligence, you generally have a three-year window to file a lawsuit in civil court. Failing to initiate legal action within this timeframe can result in the permanent forfeiture of your right to seek compensation, regardless of the merits of your case. While the three-year rule is the general standard, there are specific exceptions and circumstances that can alter this deadline. For instance, if the injured party is a minor (under 18 years old) or is deemed legally incapacitated at the time of the injury, the statute of limitations may be tolled, meaning the clock does not start running until they turn 18 or their incapacity is resolved. Additionally, the discovery rule can apply in certain situations, particularly in cases where the injury or its cause is not immediately apparent. Under the discovery rule, the three-year period may begin when the injured party discovers, or reasonably should have discovered, both the injury and its cause. This is particularly relevant in cases like medical malpractice or latent injuries where symptoms may not manifest until much later. It is also important to note that claims against governmental entities in New Mexico fall under the New Mexico Tort Claims Act, which has a significantly shorter notice period of 90 days from the date of the alleged negligence. This notice must be in writing and describe the details of the claim. Missing this 90-day notice period can also bar a claim, even if the three-year statute of limitations for filing the lawsuit has not yet expired.",
