          "title": "Statute of Limitations in New Hampshire",
          "content": "In New Hampshire, the statute of limitations for most personal injury claims is generally three years from the date the injury occurred [2] [4] [5] [6] [10] [11] [12] [13] [14] [15]. This means that if you've been injured due to someone else's negligence, you typically have a three-year window to file a lawsuit in civil court. This deadline is codified under N.H. Rev. Stat. \u00a7 508:4(I) [10].\n\nHowever, there are important exceptions to this general rule. For instance, if the injured party is a minor, the statute of limitations may be tolled, meaning the three-year period might not begin until their 18th birthday [11]. Medical malpractice cases also have specific rules, often allowing for a two-year period from the date of discovery of the injury, or four years from the date of the injury itself, whichever is later [1]. It is crucial to understand that missing this deadline, regardless of the circumstances, almost invariably results in the forfeiture of your right to pursue compensation for your injuries. Therefore, consulting with a New Hampshire personal injury attorney as soon as possible after an accident is highly recommended to ensure all deadlines are met and your rights are protected.",
