          "title": "Statute of Limitations in North Carolina",
          "content": "In North Carolina, individuals pursuing personal injury claims must adhere to a strict legal deadline known as the statute of limitations. Generally, the law mandates a **three-year** period to file a lawsuit in court, commencing from the date the injury becomes apparent [1]. This crucial deadline applies to a broad spectrum of personal injury cases, including those arising from motor vehicle accidents, incidents on dangerous or poorly maintained properties (premises liability), injuries caused by defective products (product liability), and even dog bites [1]. It is imperative for potential plaintiffs to be aware of this timeframe, as failing to initiate legal action within this period can result in the permanent forfeiture of their right to seek compensation.\n\nNorth Carolina law also incorporates a version of the **\"discovery rule\"** to determine the precise commencement of the statute of limitations. According to N.C. Stat. \u00a7 1-52(16), the clock begins to run from the earlier of two dates: either when the injury actually becomes apparent, or when it reasonably *should* have been apparent to a diligent individual [1]. While in many cases, injuries are immediately evident\u2014such as a broken arm from a fall\u2014there are instances where symptoms may manifest much later, as with prolonged exposure to harmful chemicals. In such complex scenarios, the discovery rule may extend the period for filing a claim. However, relying on this rule often entails a significant legal challenge, as defendants and courts may scrutinize the claimant's diligence in discovering the injury [1].\n\nFurthermore, North Carolina imposes an absolute limit on the time to sue, irrespective of when an injury is discovered, through **statutes of repose**. In most personal injury cases, this means that the lawsuit must be filed no later than **10 years** after the last action or inaction by the defendant that caused the harm [1]. This statute of repose acts as an overarching deadline, preventing claims from being brought indefinitely, even if the injury was not discovered within the initial three-year period. Given the complexities of these deadlines, consulting with an experienced North Carolina personal injury attorney is highly recommended to ensure all legal timeframes are met.",
