          "title": "Statute of Limitations in Utah",
          "content": "In Utah, the statute of limitations for most personal injury claims is **four years** from the date of the injury [1]. This deadline is crucial, as failing to file a lawsuit within this timeframe typically results in the forfeiture of your right to pursue compensation. \n\nHowever, there are specific exceptions to this general rule. For instance, wrongful death lawsuits and claims involving defective products generally have a **two-year** statute of limitations [1]. Medical malpractice cases also typically adhere to a two-year limit, but with unique caveats: if a foreign object is left in the body, the claim must be filed within one year of discovery, and if misconduct was deliberately concealed, the claimant has one year from the discovery of the misconduct [1]. Claims against government entities also have a two-year limit, but require a notice of claim to be filed with the government within that period, followed by a 60-day response period before a lawsuit can proceed [1]. The 'discovery rule' can also extend the filing deadline in certain situations, such as when the injury or its cause is not immediately apparent, like in cases involving toxic chemicals or dangerous pharmaceuticals [1]. For minors or individuals deemed 'mentally incompetent,' the statute of limitations is paused until the condition ceases, at which point the standard timeframe begins [1]. It is imperative to consult with a personal injury attorney to understand how these complex rules and exceptions apply to your specific case, ensuring that critical deadlines are not missed and your right to seek justice is preserved.",
