          "text": "In personal injury law, an appeal is a formal request made to a higher court to review a decision made by a lower court or jury. This process is initiated by a party who is dissatisfied with the original outcome, believing that legal errors or procedural mistakes occurred during the trial. An appeal is not a retrial of the case; instead, the appellate court examines the trial record to determine if the law was applied correctly and if due process was followed. If the appellate court finds significant errors, it may reverse the lower court's decision, send the case back for a new trial, or modify the judgment. This can be a crucial step for injured individuals seeking justice when they feel the initial ruling was unfair or legally flawed."
